1. A contract that holds assets in form of tokens. An example of such an asset might be an Ether, Euro or Dai. The tokens are always issued by a token issuer. This can either be a smart contract or a human being (i.e. a self-sovereign wealth management organisation).

2. A pool of lenders that will deposit assets and borrow new assets based on the ratio. Deposits are used to get loans at rates that the asset issuers may have set in advance.

3. A contract that holds funds from previous lending periods and keeps it safe by performing liquidations, which reduce the available supply of tokens by setting them back into the pool.

